{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643116"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:49:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:49:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17988"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17988"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79247"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10702"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17988"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64589"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10266"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79247"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlycogen stored in skeletal muscle can be rapidly broken down to provide energy during exercise. This process must be tightly regulated to match energy supply with demand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is the primary regulator of skeletal muscle glycogenolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid hormones","Glucagon","Cortisol","Insulin","Calcium ions"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary regulator of skeletal muscle glycogenolysis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E. During muscle contraction, calcium is released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, which activates phosphorylase kinase. This enzyme then activates glycogen phosphorylase, leading to the breakdown of glycogen into glucose-1-phosphate for energy production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormones\u003C/strong\u003E influence overall metabolic rate but do not directly regulate muscle glycogenolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon\u003C/strong\u003E primarily stimulates glycogenolysis in the liver, with minimal effect on muscle tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECortisol\u003C/strong\u003E mainly affects protein metabolism and has only indirect effects on muscle glycogen metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin\u003C/strong\u003E actually inhibits glycogenolysis and promotes glycogen storage\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis calcium-mediated regulation ensures that glycogen breakdown is closely linked to muscle activity, providing energy precisely when needed during contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle glycogenolysis is primarily regulated by intracellular calcium released during muscle contraction.","Calcium ions activate phosphorylase kinase which then activates glycogen phosphorylase to break down glycogen.","Unlike liver glycogenolysis, muscle glycogen breakdown is mainly controlled by local factors rather than hormones."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17988"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T21:09:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T21:11:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10702"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79247"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","pos